Sam Ndenecho (2026-04-02 00:22:54)(Select): However, their solution is just a launcher/wrapper app, so information is still quite limited. Nothing about what specifically in their browsing sessions made them feel a certain way, or potential quantitative data (time spent, # of posts looked at).; Sam Ndenecho (2026-04-02 00:19:29)(Select): RQ3:
Pretty good paper exploring a possible intervention for teens who potentially overuse social media.

Goes through their approach to intervention, and its positive effects on the teens' sense of agency/control, and self-reflection.;

Sam Ndenecho (2026-04-11 09:13:12)(Select): Relevancy: More about RQ1, but also covers some small part of RQ2.

The study explores how maltreatment during adolescence and childhood correlates with younger teens' social media use. In particular, this study outlines differences between boys and girls, and   discusses explanations using existing knowledge in psychology.

If we are to make a wider point from this and other studies, it is that often social media is part of a self-fulfilling cycle, and it can amplify existing negative effects (or indeed positive ones, too!);

Sam Ndenecho (2026-04-12 05:45:00)(Select): Relevancy: Very relevant to RQ2. A well-designed and well-balanced sample of 13-16 year olds in the UK. We should definitely quote from this paper.

They make the argument that, for girls, most of the perceived negative effects of frequent social media use is mostly covered by cyberbullying, lack of sleep, and lack of physical activity. They couldn't really say the same for boys, so other factors may be at play.

Finally, they then make the conclusion, "Our data suggest that interventions to reduce social media use to improve mental health might be misplaced." Which is a dissenting opinion that we should feature.;
